commit.message: Bump for next development version
Bump version for Coda-8.1.5

Fix callbacks

Argument list order broke after adding a timeout to the multirpc
callback break.
Update pre-commit config and CI cache settings
Bump to development version
Bump versions to coda-8.1.4, lwp-2.17, rpc2-2.37, rvm-1.28
Merge diverged branches

We shouldn't mark an object as VASTRO when we cannot fetch it

Files pending reintegration became inaccessible whenever their
vastro flag got toggled. This should avoid marking them as such.
Add helper scripts to run testrvm and rvm_basher tests
Remove unused local variable
We need to include unistd.h for getpagesize
Some rwcdb code cleanups.

Add a goto to avoid warning.

Most gotos were only conditionally compiled so in some cases we got an
errant warning about an unused Exit label.

Fix process termination hang on pthreaded rw test

When all thread are destroyed, nothing would schedule to wake up the
sleeping main thread. Make main thread async at start of termination and
use sleep instead of yield while waiting for all threads to terminate.
Update lwp_pt API to match changes to lwp.
Disable gitlab-ci.yml linting
coda-make-certs: don't show scp progress when --quiet is passed
Syntax fixes for python-3.4

Fix reading dump files with runt symlinks.

Change how fread is called so we correctly handle reading a symlink with
no content because it hasn't been resolved yet.
Forgot to propagate the dry_run argument in codafs.cfs.setacl
Parallelize CI build
Add Gdk version constraint to gcodacon

Drop support for python2

It looks like any distribution we run on has python3 available.
Fix passing dict as default argument in gcodacon
Used 'typos' to detect and fix various incorrect spellings.
Tweak cache config for CI builds
Add pyupgrade to modernize python code
Move coda-make-certs under python scripts

Remove coda-src/vtools/up.cc

This has been in the source tree since the beginning of recorded Coda
history, but it has not been packaged in the distributed source tar
archives or compiled. There is no manpage and it contains 2 different
(conflicting) 'usage:' strings.

Its purpose seems to be to recursively copy a directory tree while
preserving mode and owner bits with the additional option of converting
directory ACLs from an old to a new format. We can use off-the-shelf
`cp` or `rsync` to do the recursive copy and I don't believe the old
ACL format exists anymore so the extra conversion step is not necessary.
check-clang-format is a script and limit it to precommit stages
